reveals how legal meaning, understood to be the outcome of a specific society, is being reworked to devalue the capacities of Indigenous societies. Addressing liberal positivism and critical postcolonial theory, Canadian Law and Indigenous Self-Determination considers the way in which Canadian jurists, working within a world circumscribed by liberal thought, have deployed the law in such a way as to attempt to remove Indigenous meaning-generating capacity.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 24. Aug 2021) 0aIndians of North AmericaxCivil rightszCanada. 0aIndians of North AmericaxLegal status, laws, etczCanada. 0aIndians of North AmericaxLegal status, laws, etc.zCanada. 0aSociological jurisprudencezCanada. 7aLAW / Indigenous Peoples.2bisacsh  aAboriginal rights.  aCanada.  aIndigenous sovereignty.  alegal analysis.  aliberal thought.  ameaning generation.  anaturalism.  aperspectives.  apostcolonialism.  asocial construction.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE COMPLETE 2019 Englishz978311061076508iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE Economics, Law & Social Sciences 2019 ENGz978311061013008iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE Law 2019z9783110606249oZDB-23-DGC08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of Toronto Press Complete eBook-Package 2019z978311065206240uhttps://doi.org/10.3138/978144262550140uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781442625501423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9781442625501.jpg  a978-3-11-061013-0  EBOOK PACKAGE Economics, Law & Social Sciences 2019 ENGb2019  a978-3-11-061076-5  EBOOK PACKAGE COMPLETE 2019 Englishb2019  a978-3-11-065206-2  University of Toronto Press Complete eBook-Package 2019b2019  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aZDB-23-DGCb2019